{"metadata": {"length": 11843, "words": 744, "reading_time_min": 3.72}, "text": "Morgan is not a man of letters; in fact, his English lacks the minimum degree of coherence. That is why I am so amazed by the words he wrote, although others have laughed. It was only the night that it happened. He suddenly had an insatiable desire to write, and taking up the pen wrote the following: \u201cI am Howard Phillips. Lives on College Street, 66, Providence, Rhode Island. On November 24th 1927 - I do not even know what year we are in - I fell asleep and had a dream; and since then it has been impossible to wake up. \u00bbMy dream began in a humid, pansy-covered, rocky landscape under a grey and autumnal sky, with a sudden cliff-face covered in lichens to the north. Impulsed by a vague curiosity, I climbed up a ledge or ledge of said precipice, then observing that on one side and the other of the walls were the black mouths of numerous swans that were ensconced in the depths of the rock plateau. \"In several places, the passage was blocked by the narrowing of the upper part of the fissure; in those places, the darkness was extraordinary, and the marrows that might be there were not discerned. In one of those dark tunnels I felt a tremendous fear, as if an inward and subtle manifestation of the abbeys were taking possession of my spirit; but the darkness was too dense to discover the source of my alarm. \u00bbLast, I came to a plateau covered with rotten rock and scarcely any land, illuminated by a weak moon that had replaced the agonizing twilight of the day. I looked about me and saw no living thing; yet I felt an odd agitation very close to me, among the murmuring twigs of the pestilential cyne that I had only recently abandoned. \"After walking a mile, I came to a tangled tangle of branches, and with tangled posts that still supported the flimsy and tangled cable of the troll. Following these roads, I came to a yellow car that bore the number 1852, with a fuel tank attached, of the double-cab type, in boga between 1900 and 1910. He was empty, though obviously about to start; he had the shackle on the cable and the air brake was squealing from time to time under the floor of the van. I climbed on board, and looked around in vain for a light switch... then I noticed the absence of the control panel, which indicated that the conductor was not there. I sat on one of the cross-bench seats. I then saw the weeds growing on the side of the left, and I saw the dark shadows of two men bending at the light of the moon. They carried the company's standard goggles, and I realized that they were the collector and the conductor. Then one of them sniffed the air, sucked in a strong breath, and lifted his face to look at the moon. The other sat on four legs ready to run to the car. \"I leapt up, sprinted out of the car and ran and ran along the mesa, until exhaustion forced me to stop... No, not because the thief was kicking his feet, but because the driver's face was a pale white blotch that was squeezing out a red tentacle like blood. ................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................ \u00bbFrom that dreadful night, all I want is to be awakened... but it hasn\u2019t been possible yet! \u00bbOn the contrary, I have discovered that I am a resident of this terrible heavenly world! That first night I walked in the silence of the morning, wandering aimlessly through the lonesome prairies. When night came, he still walked, waiting to be awakened. But suddenly I removed the malady and saw before me the old thorn... there was a horny face being lifted up and glowed strangely in the moonlight! \u00bbEvery day it happens the same. The night takes me as always to that place of horror. I have tried not to move when the moon comes out, but I must walk in my dreams, for I awake with the awe-inspiring moon shining before me; then I turn half round, and I run wildly. \u00bbOh my God! When shall I awaken?\u201d That is what Morgan wrote. I want to go to 66 College Street in Providence; but I am afraid of what I might find there. FIN \u201cThe Thing in the Moonlight\u201d, 1927", "title": "El ser bajo la luz de la luna", "author": "H. P. Lovecraft"}